        heading: 'Common MIDP Failures and How to Avoid Them',
        content: "In practice, several common failures undermine the effectiveness of the MIDP.\n\nOver-optimistic TIDP dates: task teams submit TIDPs with delivery dates that look good on paper but do not reflect their actual production capacity or internal review time. The lead appointed party should challenge unrealistic dates at TIDP review, not accept them passively.\n\nInsufficient granularity: a TIDP that lists 'all structural drawings' as a single line item with one delivery date is not useful for management. Every individual information container should have its own line item.\n\nNo dependency mapping: a MIDP that does not record inter-team dependencies cannot be used to manage critical path. When a structural delay holds up the MEP team, a dependency-aware MIDP identifies this instantly. A MIDP without dependencies does not.\n\nInfrequent updates: a MIDP that is only updated at major milestones is already out of date by the time anyone reads it. Regular — ideally fortnightly — MIDP reviews aligned with coordination meetings keep the document current.\n\nFor Revit teams, a practical connection exists between the MIDP and the Revit model breakdown. Each Revit model file that the team is responsible for should correspond to at least one line item in the TIDP, with its naming convention, target dates, and LOIN clearly recorded."
