      {
        heading: 'The Suitability Code System',
        content: "Suitability codes are short alphanumeric identifiers applied to published information containers that define the specific purpose for which the information is authorised. They appear as metadata in the CDE and are often appended to or included in the document title block.\n\nThe standard suitability codes used in ISO 19650 practice (following the UK national annex conventions widely adopted internationally) are:\n\nS0 — Work in progress. Not yet suitable for sharing. Rarely applied as a formal code since WIP information should not be in the Published area, but sometimes used in CDEs that require a status code at all stages.\n\nS1 — Suitable for coordination. The information has been checked and is ready for other disciplines to reference and coordinate against, but it is not yet approved for design or construction use.\n\nS2 — Suitable for information. Shared for the recipient's awareness. Not for design coordination or construction use.\n\nS3 — Suitable for review and comment. The information is at a stage where formal review and feedback is requested from the recipient. Comments must be formally responded to.\n\nS4 — Suitable for construction. The information has been formally approved for use by contractors in building the project. This is the highest level of authorisation for delivery-phase information.\n\nS5 — Suitable for as-built record. The information reflects what has actually been constructed. Applied to as-built documentation at the end of the construction phase.\n\nS6 — Suitable for archiving. The information is being archived as a permanent record."
      },
      {
        heading: 'Applying Suitability Codes in Practice',
        content: "Understanding when to apply each code requires judgment as well as knowledge of the definitions.\n\nS1 (Suitable for coordination) is applied when you want other disciplines to use your model as a reference for their own work, but you are not yet ready for formal approval. A structural engineer might issue S1 models early in design development so the MEP team can start routing around the structural frame, even though the structural design is not finalised.\n\nS3 (Suitable for review and comment) is applied at formal client review milestones. When the architect issues a scheme design package for client sign-off, the drawings and models carry S3. The client's review comments must be formally recorded and responded to before the next stage begins.\n\nS4 (Suitable for construction) is the most consequential code. Information carrying S4 has been formally reviewed, approved, and authorised by the appointing party for construction. Contractors are entitled to rely on S4 information. If S4 information contains errors, the liability for those errors and any resulting rework lies with the party who issued and approved it.\n\nA common mistake is applying S4 to information that has not actually been through the full approval process. This creates legal exposure. S4 should only be applied by the authorised approving party, not self-assigned by the producing team."
      },
      {
        heading: 'Transmittals and Issue Records',
        content: "A transmittal is a formal record of information being issued from one party to another. Every formal issue of information containers in a CDE workflow should be accompanied by a transmittal record that captures: the date of issue, the issuing party, the receiving party, the list of containers being issued (with their container IDs, titles, revisions, and suitability codes), the purpose of the issue, and any response required and by when.\n\nIn a modern CDE platform like Autodesk Construction Cloud, transmittals are generated automatically when information is moved from Shared to Published or when a package is formally transmitted to the appointing party. The CDE maintains a complete transmittal register that provides a fully auditable history of every formal information exchange on the project.\n\nIn simpler CDE setups, transmittals may be manual documents. Even in this case, they should be formally produced, signed, and retained. A handshake or email saying 'the drawings are on the server' is not an ISO 19650-compliant transmittal. It creates no formal record and no clear point of responsibility transfer."
      },
      {
        heading: 'Requests for Information (RFIs) Under ISO 19650',
        content: "A Request for Information (RFI) is a formal query raised by one project party when they need clarification, additional information, or a decision from another party. RFIs are one of the most common information management activities on construction projects and must be managed systematically.\n\nUnder ISO 19650, RFIs should be logged, tracked, responded to within defined timeframes, and closed out formally. The CDE or a linked project management system typically provides an RFI register.\n\nEach RFI should record: the RFI number and date, the originator and recipient, the query description and reason, the models or drawings it relates to (with container IDs), the required response date, the actual response date, the response content, and whether the response triggers a design change or a model update.\n\nRFIs that are not formally logged and tracked create information gaps. If a contractor verbally asks a question and acts on a verbal answer, there is no record of what was asked, what was answered, or whether the answer was correct. This becomes a dispute risk. Formal RFI management eliminates this risk."
      },
      {
        heading: 'Design Change Management',
        content: "Not all changes to information during a project are errors. Many changes result from legitimate design evolution — client scope changes, regulatory requirements, coordination resolutions, or value engineering.\n\nISO 19650 requires that design changes be managed through a formal change process. When a change is proposed, it should be recorded as a change request, assessed for impact on the information delivery schedule and other disciplines, approved by the appropriate party, and implemented through a controlled revision of the relevant information containers.\n\nFor Revit teams, this connects directly to how Revit model revisions are managed. When a change is approved, the relevant model files receive a new revision number (following the P or C series convention), the change is documented in the revision cloud and revision schedule on affected drawing sheets, the updated model is uploaded to WIP, checked, moved to Shared for re-coordination, and reissued through the approval cycle.\n\nTracking changes formally in the CDE means that the impact of every design change — on drawings, models, and schedules — is visible and managed. Uncontrolled changes that bypass the formal process create information inconsistency and coordination failures."
      }
